snippet.textDisplay: The specific acid in pineapple and the specific main protein in american cheese start a mild reaction, however this is accelerated by the temperature, and the lamb fat reacts in a similar way to the cheese and produces a byproduct that then speeds up the cheese’s reaction as a catalyst and additionally then reacts with that produced material to cause the flavor to become far more extreme through a secondary breakdown.  Additionally charred american cheese tends to have a bitter acrid flavor unlike other charred cheeses, and this is enhanced not complimented by the reaction you caused.  Further note: the capsaicin from the pepper likely reacted to the carbonic residue in the charred cheese to make the bitter notes even stronger yet.
snippet.textOriginal: The specific acid in pineapple and the specific main protein in american cheese start a mild reaction, however this is accelerated by the temperature, and the lamb fat reacts in a similar way to the cheese and produces a byproduct that then speeds up the cheese’s reaction as a catalyst and additionally then reacts with that produced material to cause the flavor to become far more extreme through a secondary breakdown.  Additionally charred american cheese tends to have a bitter acrid flavor unlike other charred cheeses, and this is enhanced not complimented by the reaction you caused.  Further note: the capsaicin from the pepper likely reacted to the carbonic residue in the charred cheese to make the bitter notes even stronger yet.

snippet.textDisplay:
Cheese can work with Pineapple in a burger, but not processed cheese. Hawaiian burgers are extremely common here in NZ. The way theyre made is with a slice of pineapple, grilled ham steak and sometimes a fried egg. But while the pattie/ham/egg are cooking, you put cheddar cheese down on the griddle and put the bun on top and griddle cheddar cheese into the bun that gets toasted. It works perfectly together!


KFC do actually do a hawaiian chicken burger here with processed cheese, but they seperate the cheese & pineapple with bacon, and the cheese isnt melted during the cooking, its added cold which with the cold pineapple stops it from going funny.
snippet.textOriginal:

snippet.textDisplay: The same enzyme that makes pineapple such an effective meat tenderizer, bromelain, will also react to the proteins and fat in dairy. There are ways to counteract this, such as grilling the pineapple, freeze-drying it, or treating it with capsaicin, either in pure form or boiling it with chilies. Without treatment, you're in for the taste of the sourest sour milk you've ever had the misfortune of putting in your mouth. Which, by the way, can be a fun prank to play on people - just give them a few pineapple chunks on their cornflakes and prepare to giggle.
snippet.textOriginal: The same enzyme that makes pineapple such an effective meat tenderizer, bromelain, will also react to the proteins and fat in dairy. snippet.textDisplay:
Pineapple contains an enzyme "bromelain" that dissolves protein. As processed cheese is in essence an emulsion of fat, protein and water, the pineapple juice will react with it, the acidity of the pineapple futhering the curdling even more.

Fun fact for Jamie, boiling pineapple with chili removes this effect for icecream making, as the capsaicin reacts with the bromelain.

snippet.textDisplay: I have never really liked American cheese, it's good if you need something to be melty and gooey (in the middle baby😉), like a grilled cheese for small children, but for a burger I like gouda. For this one I think I would have made up a bit of salad to put on top (carmelized onion, cabbage, peppers, tomato) I might have sliced a thin round of zucchini or eggplant and cooked that to go on the burger instead of long slices. If you guys kept the mushrooms you could have made it into a mushroom swiss burger, or maybe into a black and blue. Either way I'm definitely going to try a chorizo-lamb mince next time. Loved the reactions you guys had! I would actually love to see you guys do a battle to fix a relay recipe like this one. I'm really curious what everyone would do differently.
